df=pd.read_csv("/Users/linshuyu/Downloads/drone.csv")
df.info(),df.head()

# PART (a):
# Define feature columns
defined_features = ['voltage_v', 'voltage_filtered_v', 'current_a', 'current_filtered_a', 'discharged_mah', 'remaining', 'scale', 'load', 'ram_usage']

target_variable = 'warning'

# Extract data subset
df_selected = df[defined_features + [target_variable]]

# Display data summary
df_selected.describe().transpose()

# Compute the correlation matrix
corr_matrix = df_selected.corr()

# Plot the correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm", fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Feature Correlation")
plt.show()

# Encode the target variable
le = LabelEncoder()
df[target_variable] = le.fit_transform(df[target_variable])

# Compute correlation with the target variable
correlation = df.corr()[target_variable].drop(target_variable).abs()

# Select the top 6 features most correlated with the target variable
selected_features = correlation.nlargest(6).index.tolist()
print("Selected Features:", selected_features)


# PART (b):
# Alternative visualization of feature distributions by warning level
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=3, ncols=3, figsize=(14, 10))
fig.suptitle("Feature Distribution by Warning Levels", fontsize=14)

for ax, col in zip(axes.flat, defined_features):
    sns.histplot(df, x=col, hue="warning", bins=30, kde=True, ax=ax, element="step", common_norm=False)
    ax.set_title(col)

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.96])
plt.show()

# Data Discretization: Convert continuous variables into categorical data and include the warning variable
def make_discrete_drone(df):

    discrete_df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    # Discretize voltage (voltage_v and voltage_filtered_v)
    voltage_labels = ['1. Low (<16V)', '2. Normal (16-18V)', '3. High (18-20V)', '4. Very High (>20V)']
    discrete_df['voltage_v'] = pd.cut(df['voltage_v'], bins=[0, 16, 18, 20, float('inf')], labels=voltage_labels, precision=2)
    discrete_df['voltage_filtered_v'] = pd.cut(df['voltage_filtered_v'], bins=[0, 16, 18, 20, float('inf')], labels=voltage_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Discretize current (current_a and current_filtered_a)
    current_labels = ['1. Very Low (<5A)', '2. Low (5-12A)', '3. Normal (12-18A)', '4. High (>18A)']
    discrete_df['current_a'] = pd.cut(df['current_a'], bins=[0, 5, 12, 18, float('inf')], labels=current_labels, precision=2)
    discrete_df['current_filtered_a'] = pd.cut(df['current_filtered_a'], bins=[0, 5, 12, 18, float('inf')], labels=current_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Discretize remaining battery percentage
    remaining_labels = ['1. Empty (0)', '2. Low (0-0.3)', '3. Medium (0.3-0.6)', '4. High (0.6-1)']
    discrete_df['remaining'] = pd.cut(df['remaining'], bins=[-0.1, 0, 0.3, 0.6, 1], labels=remaining_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Discretize scaling factor
    scale_labels = ['1. Normal (~1.15)', '2. Deviated (<1.05)']
    discrete_df['scale'] = pd.cut(df['scale'], bins=[0, 1.05, float('inf')], labels=scale_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Include the warning variable, assuming it is already categorical
    discrete_df['warning'] = df['warning'].astype('object')
    
    # Convert all columns to object type (useful for Bayesian network analysis)
    discrete_df = discrete_df.astype('object')
    
    return discrete_df

# Perform discretization, including the warning variable
cat_df_drone = make_discrete_drone(df)

# Data Statistics: Check the category distribution for each discrete variable
for column in cat_df_drone.columns:
    count_df = cat_df_drone.groupby(column)[column].count().reset_index(name='Count')
    print(f"Feature '{column}' distribution：")
    print(count_df.to_dict(orient='records'))
    print("===================================")

# Data Splitting: Split the data into training and testing sets

# Remove missing values and use 80% of the data for training
training_data, testing_data = train_test_split(cat_df_drone.dropna(), test_size=0.2, random_state=20)

# Bayesian Network Modeling: Structure Learning and Parameter Learning (including the warning node)
# Use Hill Climb Search for structure learning, with k2score as the scoring method
hc = HillClimbSearch(training_data)
estimated_model = hc.estimate(scoring_method='k2score')

# Build a Bayesian Network model, including the warning variable in the network structure
model = BayesianNetwork(estimated_model.edges())
print("Learned network structure：")
print(model.edges())

# Parameter learning: Use BayesianEstimator with BDeu prior (equivalent sample size set to 10)
model.fit(data=training_data,
          estimator=BayesianEstimator,
          prior_type='BDeu',
          equivalent_sample_size=10)

# Output the Conditional Probability Distributions (CPDs) for each node
print("\nConditional Probability Distributions (CPDs) for each node: ")
for cpd in model.get_cpds():
    print(f"CPD for variable {cpd.variable}:")
    print(cpd)
    print("-----------------------------------")


# Model Visualization: Plot the Bayesian Network structure including the warning node
plt.figure(figsize=(6,6))
G = nx.DiGraph()
G.add_edges_from(model.edges())
G.add_nodes_from(model.nodes)
pos = nx.circular_layout(G)
nx.draw_networkx(G,
                 pos=pos,
                 with_labels=True,
                 node_size=2000,
                 arrowsize=30,
                 alpha=0.7,
                 font_weight="bold",
                 width=2.0)
plt.title("Bayesian Network Structure (including warning)")
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()


# PART (C):
accuracy_dict = {}

for column in testing_data.columns:
    if column == 'warning':
        continue
    
    predict_data = testing_data.copy()
    predict_data.drop(column, axis=1, inplace=True)
    y_pred = model.predict(predict_data)

    accuracy = accuracy_score(testing_data[column], y_pred)
    print(f'{column} Accuracy score: {accuracy}')

    accuracy_dict[column] = accuracy

# XGBoost (Poor recall for warning 2 due to insufficient data)
# Define features and target variable
X = df[selected_features]
y = df["warning"]

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets (stratify ensures class proportions are maintained)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Compute class weights
class_counts = y_train.value_counts()
total_samples = len(y_train)
class_weights = {c: total_samples / class_counts[c] for c in class_counts.index}

# Generate sample weights
sample_weight = y_train.map(class_weights)

# Train XGBoost model (handling class imbalance)
xgb_model = XGBClassifier(
    objective="multi:softmax",  # Multi-class classification
    num_class=len(y_train.unique()),  # Set number of classes
    eval_metric="mlogloss",  # Avoid XGBoost's default RMSE
    n_estimators=200,
    learning_rate=0.05,
    max_depth=2,
    reg_lambda=10,  # L2 regularization (prevents overfitting)
    reg_alpha=5,  # L1 regularization (prevents overfitting)
    random_state=42
)

xgb_model.fit(X_train, y_train, sample_weight=sample_weight)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print(classification_rep)
print(conf_matrix)
y_train_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_train)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

print(f"Training Accuracy: {train_acc:.4f}")

# XGBoost code balances class distribution by adjusting warning 0, 1, 2 to 500 samples each and reducing warning 3 to 20%
X = df[selected_features]
y = df["warning"]


# Reduce the number of class 3 samples to balance the dataset
df_class_3 = df[df["warning"] == 3].sample(frac=0.2, random_state=42)  # Keep only 20% of class 3
df_other_classes = df[df["warning"] != 3]

df_balanced = pd.concat([df_class_3, df_other_classes]).sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

# Redefine X and y
X = df_balanced[selected_features]
y = df_balanced["warning"]

# Split the dataset again (ensure class proportions are maintained)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Check original class distribution
print("Original class distribution:", Counter(y_train))

# Use SMOTE to oversample class 0, class 1, and class 2
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy={0: 500, 1: 500, 2: 500}, random_state=42, k_neighbors=1)  
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Check new class distribution
print("Resampled class distribution:", Counter(y_train_resampled))

# Compute new class weights
class_counts = y_train_resampled.value_counts()
total_samples = len(y_train_resampled)
class_weights = {c: total_samples / class_counts[c] for c in class_counts.index}

# Generate sample weights
sample_weight = y_train_resampled.map(class_weights)

# Train the XGBoost model (handling class imbalance)
xgb_model = XGBClassifier(
    objective="multi:softmax",  
    num_class=len(y_train_resampled.unique()),  
    eval_metric="mlogloss",  
    n_estimators=100, 
    learning_rate=0.03, 
    max_depth=3,  
    reg_lambda=20,  
    reg_alpha=10, 
    random_state=42
)

# Train the model
xgb_model.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled, sample_weight=sample_weight)

# Make predictions
y_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_rep)
print("Confusion Matrix:\n", conf_matrix)

# Calculate training accuracy
y_train_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_train_resampled)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train_resampled, y_train_pred)
print(f"Training Accuracy: {train_acc:.4f}")

In Part (a), numerical variables (e.g., voltage, current, remaining power) and the target variable “warning” are specified, and the corresponding columns are extracted from the original dataset. We then use describe() to obtain a statistical summary for each feature, calculate the correlation matrix, and visualize it as a heatmap to observe inter-feature relationships. Next, LabelEncoder converts the target variable into a numeric format, and correlations between each feature and the target are computed to select the six most relevant features. In Part (b), seaborn’s histplot creates subplots displaying the distribution of each numerical feature grouped by “warning,” which helps in visualizing feature distributions under different warning states. To prepare the data for Bayesian network analysis, continuous variables (such as voltage, current, remaining power, and scale) are discretized into categorical data based on predefined intervals and labels while retaining the warning variable. All fields are then converted to the object type. Groupby and count operations are performed to check the category distribution of each discrete variable, ensuring that the classifications meet expectations. Finally, the processed data is split into an 80% training set and a 20% test set. For Bayesian network modeling, Hill Climb Search with k2score is used for structure learning to estimate the edges between nodes. Then, the Bayesian Estimator with a BDeu prior estimates the conditional probability distributions (CPDs) for each node, which are printed out. A directed graph is constructed using networkx and plotted with matplotlib to display the network structure, including the warning node. In the prediction phase, the Bayesian network is used to predict each feature (except warning) in the test set, and accuracy is calculated to evaluate its performance. Recognizing that similar features (filtered and unfiltered voltage and current) might lead to overfitting, the four most representative features are chosen to build a Random Forest classifier. Its training and evaluation output accuracy, a classification report, a confusion matrix, and a feature importance chart. Although the Random Forest achieves high accuracy, the limited samples for warnings 0 to 2 necessitate further improvement. Therefore, using an XGBoost model to train on the original data using calculated sample weights; then, by downsampling warning 3 and using SMOTE to augment the other classes to 500 samples, the data is balanced and a new XGBoost model is trained. This approach effectively reduces prediction bias due to data imbalance, yielding more accurate results.

# Data Discretization: Convert continuous variables into categorical data and include the warning variable
def make_discrete_drone(df):

    discrete_df = pd.DataFrame()
    
    # Discretize voltage (voltage_v and voltage_filtered_v)
    voltage_labels = ['1. Low (<16V)', '2. Normal (16-18V)', '3. High (18-20V)', '4. Very High (>20V)']
    discrete_df['voltage_v'] = pd.cut(df['voltage_v'], bins=[0, 16, 18, 20, float('inf')], labels=voltage_labels, precision=2)
    discrete_df['voltage_filtered_v'] = pd.cut(df['voltage_filtered_v'], bins=[0, 16, 18, 20, float('inf')], labels=voltage_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Discretize current (current_a and current_filtered_a)
    current_labels = ['1. Very Low (<5A)', '2. Low (5-12A)', '3. Normal (12-18A)', '4. High (>18A)']
    discrete_df['current_a'] = pd.cut(df['current_a'], bins=[0, 5, 12, 18, float('inf')], labels=current_labels, precision=2)
    discrete_df['current_filtered_a'] = pd.cut(df['current_filtered_a'], bins=[0, 5, 12, 18, float('inf')], labels=current_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Discretize remaining battery percentage
    remaining_labels = ['1. Empty (0)', '2. Low (0-0.3)', '3. Medium (0.3-0.6)', '4. High (0.6-1)']
    discrete_df['remaining'] = pd.cut(df['remaining'], bins=[-0.1, 0, 0.3, 0.6, 1], labels=remaining_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Discretize scaling factor
    scale_labels = ['1. Normal (~1.15)', '2. Deviated (<1.05)']
    discrete_df['scale'] = pd.cut(df['scale'], bins=[0, 1.05, float('inf')], labels=scale_labels, precision=2)
    
    # Include the warning variable, assuming it is already categorical
    discrete_df['warning'] = df['warning'].astype('object')
    
    # Convert all columns to object type (useful for Bayesian network analysis)
    discrete_df = discrete_df.astype('object')
    
    return discrete_df

# Perform discretization, including the warning variable
cat_df_drone = make_discrete_drone(df)

# XGBoost (Poor recall for warning 2 due to insufficient data)
# Define features and target variable
X = df[selected_features]
y = df["warning"]

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets (stratify ensures class proportions are maintained)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Compute class weights
class_counts = y_train.value_counts()
total_samples = len(y_train)
class_weights = {c: total_samples / class_counts[c] for c in class_counts.index}

# Generate sample weights
sample_weight = y_train.map(class_weights)

# Train XGBoost model (handling class imbalance)
xgb_model = XGBClassifier(
    objective="multi:softmax",  # Multi-class classification
    num_class=len(y_train.unique()),  # Set number of classes
    eval_metric="mlogloss",  # Avoid XGBoost's default RMSE
    n_estimators=200,
    learning_rate=0.05,
    max_depth=2,
    reg_lambda=10,  # L2 regularization (prevents overfitting)
    reg_alpha=5,  # L1 regularization (prevents overfitting)
    random_state=42
)

xgb_model.fit(X_train, y_train, sample_weight=sample_weight)

# Predict on the test set
y_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print(classification_rep)
print(conf_matrix)
y_train_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_train)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)

print(f"Training Accuracy: {train_acc:.4f}")

# XGBoost code balances class distribution by adjusting warning 0, 1, 2 to 500 samples each and reducing warning 3 to 20%
X = df[selected_features]
y = df["warning"]


# Reduce the number of class 3 samples to balance the dataset
df_class_3 = df[df["warning"] == 3].sample(frac=0.2, random_state=42)  # Keep only 20% of class 3
df_other_classes = df[df["warning"] != 3]

df_balanced = pd.concat([df_class_3, df_other_classes]).sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

# Redefine X and y
X = df_balanced[selected_features]
y = df_balanced["warning"]

# Split the dataset again (ensure class proportions are maintained)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42)

# Check original class distribution
print("Original class distribution:", Counter(y_train))

# Use SMOTE to oversample class 0, class 1, and class 2
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy={0: 500, 1: 500, 2: 500}, random_state=42, k_neighbors=1)  
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Check new class distribution
print("Resampled class distribution:", Counter(y_train_resampled))

# Compute new class weights
class_counts = y_train_resampled.value_counts()
total_samples = len(y_train_resampled)
class_weights = {c: total_samples / class_counts[c] for c in class_counts.index}

# Generate sample weights
sample_weight = y_train_resampled.map(class_weights)

# Train the XGBoost model (handling class imbalance)
xgb_model = XGBClassifier(
    objective="multi:softmax",  
    num_class=len(y_train_resampled.unique()),  
    eval_metric="mlogloss",  
    n_estimators=100, 
    learning_rate=0.03, 
    max_depth=3,  
    reg_lambda=20,  
    reg_alpha=10, 
    random_state=42
)

# Train the model
xgb_model.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled, sample_weight=sample_weight)

# Make predictions
y_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
classification_rep = classification_report(y_test, y_pred)
conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
print("Classification Report:\n", classification_rep)
print("Confusion Matrix:\n", conf_matrix)

# Calculate training accuracy
y_train_pred = xgb_model.predict(X_train_resampled)
train_acc = accuracy_score(y_train_resampled, y_train_pred)
print(f"Training Accuracy: {train_acc:.4f}")
